\begin_layout Section
Monetary Theory and Policy: Foundations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main question is: what is the target (optimal) inflation rate? Most
 advanced countries (starting with New Zealand in the early 90s) adopted
 the policy of targeting a 2% inflation rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today monetary policy is focused on the interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
What is Money?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A medium of exchange (a legal tender) and a unit of account which stores
 value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The money consists of cash produced by the CB, its reserves and close substitute
s (deposits):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=Cash+Demand\,deposits
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Value of Money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Long ago, each printed dollar was equal a ceratin amount of gold (gold standard
 - commodity money), which was gradually replaced by Fiat money in the 20th
 century.
 Its advantage is having zero cost to print (no gold cover needed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The CB can, by law, print (or detsroy) as much money as needed to reach
 its goal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What makes Fiat money acceptable, why do people go on holding it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Money is an asset with a nominal interest rate of 0%.
 The cost of holding money is the interest gained on an alternative asset
 with a similar risk (safe asset - government bond).
 The higher the interest rate - the more expensive it is to hold liquid
 cash, decreasing the demand for money.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interest rate can be negative (the CB takes money for holding the cash).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interest Rate Determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the 80s, the short-run nominal interest rate is set by the CBs, with
 the quantity of money (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

) determined endogenously.
 The bank can determine the interest rate, by providing loans/deposits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory of demand (Friedman & Sidrauski): individuals derive increasing
 utility from consumption and real balance of money (for liquidity and transacti
on services).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key assumption is that in the long-run, real values are not affected by
 monetary polocy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The long-run real value of money that maximizes utility is such that 
\series bold
maximizes the value of cash
\series default
 - at a point where the marginal utility is zero.
 Maximizing the value of money means that the long-run nominal interest
 rate should be 0%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, no one implements it.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

, the long-run optimal inflation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}=-r$
\end_inset

.
 The long-run real interest rate equals the marginal product of capital
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.5\%-2\%$
\end_inset

) requiring the inflation to be 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\%$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.5\%$
\end_inset

 (deflation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Neutrality of Money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The quantity theory states that the monetary policy cannot do any good in
 the long-run (money increase leads to price increase).
 The CBs believed that theory in the great depression.
 Friedman stated in a later paper (1933) that during a crisis, money supply
 shall be increased in order to prevent deflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key lesson of the great depression is: 
\series bold
accommodative policy can disconnect the relations of over-indebtedness and
 deflation
\series default
, thus preventing a deep recession.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inflation therefore should not be negative, because a 
\series bold
deflation causes recession
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a question is how to avoid a deflation in the long run, given a negative
 shock to the economy? - The long-run interest rate 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}=\pi^{*}+r$
\end_inset

 should be positive.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is independent, 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 effectively determines 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{*}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 must be a bit above 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a crisis, 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 is actually negative, to enable the households and business get out of
 it (as a short-term policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 2% is chosen to allow some space for an accommodative policy, but not
 too much.
 It is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

maximum inflation allowed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in order not to get too close to 0% nominal rate.
\end_layout

